<li role="presentation"><a href='?term="Stat%20Med"[jour]' class="usa-link" role="menuitem" data-add-to-search="true">Add to search</a></li>
</ul></nav></section><section class="front-matter"><div class="ameta p font-secondary font-xs">
<hgroup><h1>A multivariate discrete failure time model for the analysis of infant motor development</h1></hgroup><div class="cg p">
<a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Neelon%20B"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id1"><span class="name western">Brian Neelon</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id1">
<h3><span class="name western">Brian Neelon</span></h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>1</sup>Department of Public Health Sciences, Medical University of South Carolina, Charleston, South Carolina</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Neelon%20B"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Brian Neelon</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>1</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Shoaibi%20A"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id2"><span class="name western">Azza Shoaibi</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id2">
<h3><span class="name western">Azza Shoaibi</span></h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>1</sup>Department of Public Health Sciences, Medical University of South Carolina, Charleston, South Carolina</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Shoaibi%20A"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Azza Shoaibi</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>1</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Benjamin-Neelon%20SE"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id3"><span class="name western">Sara E Benjamin-Neelon</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id3">
<h3><span class="name western">Sara E Benjamin-Neelon</span></h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>1</sup>Department of Public Health Sciences, Medical University of South Carolina, Charleston, South Carolina</div>
<div class="p">
<sup>2</sup>Department of Health, Behavior and Society, Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health, Baltimore, Maryland</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Benjamin-Neelon%20SE"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Sara E Benjamin-Neelon</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>1,</sup><sup>2</sup>
</div>
<ul class="d-buttons inline-list">
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="aip_a" aria-expanded="false">Author information</button></li>
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="anp_a" aria-expanded="false">Article notes</button></li>
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="clp_a" aria-expanded="false">Copyright and License information</button></li>
</ul>
<div class="d-panels font-secondary-light">
<div id="aip_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none">
<div class="p" id="A1">
<sup>1</sup>Department of Public Health Sciences, Medical University of South Carolina, Charleston, South Carolina</div>
<div id="A2">
<sup>2</sup>Department of Health, Behavior and Society, Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health, Baltimore, Maryland</div>
<div class="author-notes p"><div class="fn" id="CR1">
<sup>✉</sup><p class="display-inline"><strong>Correspondence:</strong> Brian Neelon, Department of Public Health Sciences, Medical University of South Carolina, Charleston, SC 29425. <span>neelon@musc.edu</span></p>
</div></div>
</div>
<div id="anp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none"><div class="notes p"><section id="historyarticle-meta1" class="history"><p>Issue date 2019 Apr 30.</p></section></div></div>
<div id="clp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none"><div class="p"><a href="/about/copyright/" class="usa-link">PMC Copyright notice</a></div></div>
</div>
<div>PMCID: PMC6445681  NIHMSID: NIHMS1000672  PMID: <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30484904/" class="usa-link">30484904</a>
</div>
<div class="ra xbox p" role="complementary" aria-label="Related or updated information about this article"><div>The publisher's version of this article is available at <a href="https://doi.org/10.1002/sim.8055" class="usa-link usa-link--external" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Stat Med</a>
</div></div>
</div></section></section><section aria-label="Article content"><section class="body main-article-body"><section class="abstract" id="ABS1"><h2>Abstract</h2>
<p id="P1">We develop a multivariate discrete failure time model for the analysis of infant motor development. We use the model to jointly evaluate the time (in months) to achievement of three well-established motor milestones: sitting up, crawling, and walking. The model includes a subject-specific latent factor that reflects underlying heterogeneity in the population and accounts for within-subject dependence across the milestones. The factor loadings and covariate effects are allowed to vary flexibly across milestones, and the milestones are permitted to have unique at-risk intervals corresponding to different developmental windows. We adopt a Bayesian inferential approach and develop a convenient data-augmented Gibbs sampler for posterior computation. We conduct simulation studies to illustrate key features of the model and use the model to analyze data from the Nurture study, a birth cohort examining infant health and development during the first year of life.</p>
<section id="kwd-group1" class="kwd-group"><p><strong>Keywords:</strong> discrete failure time model, grouped survival data, healthy eating index, latent factor model, maternal diet, motor milestones</p></section></section><section id="S1"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">1 |. INTRODUCTION</h2>
<p id="P2">Infant gross motor development is an important predictor of long-term health. Earlier achievement of gross motor milestones, such as sitting up, crawling, and walking, is associated with improved language abilities, cognitive function, and educational attainment later in childhood and into adulthood.<sup><a href="#R1" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R1">1</a>–<a href="#R3" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R3">3</a></sup> Earlier motor milestone achievement may also help prevent later obesity.<sup><a href="#R4" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R4">4</a></sup> Conversely, delayed motor milestone achievement has been associated with increased sedentary time and lower levels of physical activity in later childhood<sup><a href="#R5" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R5">5</a></sup> and even psychiatric disorders such as schizophrenia in adulthood.<sup><a href="#R6" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R6">6</a></sup> Thus, it is of clinical and public health importance to identify determinants of delayed motor achievement that are suitable targets for intervention.</p>
<p id="P3">Motor development is influenced by both biological and behavioral factors. Predictors of motor milestone achievement include infant birth weight and gestational age,<sup><a href="#R1" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R1">1</a></sup> breastfeeding,<sup><a href="#R1" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R1">1</a></sup> and gestational diabetes.<sup><a href="#R7" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R7">7</a></sup> Previous studies have also assessed nutrient intake during pregnancy and motor development.<sup><a href="#R8" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R8">8</a>,<a href="#R9" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R9">9</a></sup> However, these studies have focused on specific components of maternal diet (eg, fish intake) rather than diet quality as a whole. To our knowledge, no prior studies have examined overall diet quality in pregnancy and offspring motor development, even though there is strong evidence that maternal diet is an important predictor of fetal development,<sup><a href="#R10" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R10">10</a></sup> which may, in turn, affect motor milestone achievement.</p>
<p id="P4">There are, however, a number of statistical challenges associated with the analysis of infant motor development. First, clinical researchers commonly treat time to milestone achievement as a continuous random variable and base their analyses on accelerated failure time models with underlying Weibull or log-logistic distributions.<sup><a href="#R11" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R11">11</a>,<a href="#R12" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R12">12</a></sup> However, milestones are typically recorded up to the nearest month during infancy. Because the data are grouped into discrete time intervals, it is often preferable to analyze the data using a discrete or “grouped” time-to-event model that can accommodate the excessive number of ties that ensue<sup><a href="#R13" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R13">13</a>–<a href="#R15" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R15">15</a></sup> (see the work of Hedeker et al<sup><a href="#R14" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R14">14</a></sup> for further discussion). Second, the milestones can have unique durations corresponding to different biologically plausible developmental windows. For example, according to the World Health Organization (WHO),<sup><a href="#R16" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R16">16</a></sup> over 99% of infants sit up between 3 and 10 months of age, crawl between 5 and 14 months, and walk between 8 and 18 months (a small percentage of infants advance directly to walking without crawling). The probability of achieving milestones outside of these windows is effectively zero. Thus, a suitable model for motor development should permit unique discrete “at-risk” intervals for each milestone. Third, covariates are likely to impact milestones differently. For example, healthy maternal diet and breastfeeding may be associated with earlier walking and crawling, but later sitting up. Hence, an appropriate model should have the flexibility to accommodate milestone-specific, time-varying, and time-invariant covariates and covariate effects. Finally, previous studies on infant motor development have modeled milestones independently,<sup><a href="#R11" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R11">11</a>,<a href="#R12" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R12">12</a></sup> even though they are likely to be highly correlated.<sup><a href="#R17" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R17">17</a></sup> For example, infants who crawl early may tend to walk early as well. Therefore, a statistical analysis of developmental milestones should account for this within-subject association. This can be accomplished, for instance, by including a subject-specific frailty term that induces within-subject dependence and accounts for infants’ propensities to achieve milestones at different rates.</p>
<p id="P5">To address this last challenge, several authors have proposed random effect models for correlated sequential, discrete, and grouped survival data. Tutz<sup><a href="#R18" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R18">18</a></sup> developed a sequential Rasch model for item-response analysis. Ten Have and Uttal<sup><a href="#R13" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R13">13</a></sup> proposed a multivariate continuation ratio model with subject-specific random effects. Ten Have<sup><a href="#R19" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R19">19</a></sup> developed a similar model for ordinal discrete survival data with ordered survival and failure states. More recently, Hedeker et al<sup><a href="#R14" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R14">14</a></sup> introduced a multilevel discrete failure time (DFT) model for grouped survival data with a random intercept to account for clustering.</p>
<p id="P6">We build on this work to develop a flexible DFT model for the analysis of infant motor development. Our model has several appealing features. First, we permit milestone-specific covariate effects, thus allowing variables such as birth weight and breastfeeding to impact milestones in unique ways. Next, we introduce a subject-specific frailty term that is also allowed to have differential effects on each milestone. In this sense, our model can be viewed as a latent factor model with milestone-specific factor loadings. Third, our model can easily accommodate time-dependent covariates and covariate effects, relaxing proportionality assumptions commonly made in time-to-event analyses. Finally, the model can be conveniently fit in either a frequentist or Bayesian inferential framework, the latter using a computationally tractable data-augmentation algorithm. We conduct simulation studies to examine the performance of the model and apply it to data from the Nurture study, a birth cohort examining infant health and development in the first year of life.</p></section><section id="S2"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">2 |. THE NURTURE STUDY</h2>
<p id="P7">The Nurture study is a birth cohort of predominately black women and their infants residing in the southeastern United States conducted between 2013 and 2016.<sup><a href="#R20" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R20">20</a></sup> The aim of the study was to identify factors related to feeding, physical activity and motor development, sleep, and stress that contribute to excessive weight gain in infancy. Women enrolled during pregnancy and provided additional informed consent for their infants to participate in the study shortly after birth. The Institutional Review Board of Duke University Medical Center approved this study and its protocol.</p>
<p id="P8">The study followed mothers and infants for 12 months after birth to collect data on maternal feeding practices, such as breastfeeding; infant weight, physical activity, and gross motor development; infant sleep behavior; and indicators of infant stress. Information on infant motor milestone achievement was collected monthly, either by automated interactive voice response telephone interviews or by home visits. Each month, mothers reported whether their infants achieved each of three gross motor milestones: sitting up without assistance, crawling using all four limbs and walking without assistance. We derived developmentally appropriate intervals for achievement of motor milestones using the WHO windows for motor milestone achievement: 3 to 10 months for sitting up, 5 to 14 months for crawling, and 8 to 18 months for walking. These developmental windows are consistent with our previous study examining achievement of gross motor milestones and later adiposity.<sup><a href="#R4" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R4">4</a></sup></p>
<p id="P9">The goal of our analysis was to examine associations between maternal diet quality during pregnancy and subsequent motor development. To assess maternal diet quality in pregnancy, mothers completed the Block Food Frequency Questionnaire (FFQ)<sup><a href="#R21" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R21">21</a></sup> between 20 and 36 weeks’ gestation. We scored responses to the FFQ using the Alternate Healthy Eating Index<sup><a href="#R22" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R22">22</a></sup> modified for pregnancy (AHEI-P).<sup><a href="#R23" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R23">23</a></sup> The AHEI-P quantifies diet quality based on the consumption of both nutrients (eg, calcium) and individual foods (eg, vegetables). The original AHEI-P did not include a category for nuts/soy/beans because these were not previously recommended for pregnant mothers. However, because current recommendations no longer include these restrictions, we incorporated the nuts/soy/beans category into our assessment per the original AHEI. Per protocol, we assigned a score of 0 to 10 points for each AHEI-P category based on recommended intake levels. After including the nuts/soy/beans category, the AHEI-P scores ranged from 0 to 100, with higher scores indicating better diet quality.</p>
<p id="P10">Of the 666 infants enrolled in the study, 20% had no milestone or diet data and were excluded from the analysis. We excluded an additional eight records with milestones that fell clearly outside the WHO windows (eg, walking in month 1 or 2), resulting in a final sample of 526 infants. <a href="#T1" class="usa-link">Table 1</a> presents summary statistics for maternal and infant characteristics included in our analysis. Infants were predominately black, and just over half were male. The sample median birth weight z-score was slightly below the median for the WHO population. The median ages for sitting up, crawling, and walking were 6, 8, and 12 months, respectively. AHEI-P scores in the sample ranged from 19 to 97 with a mean of 69 and a median of 70, which are slightly higher than those reported in prior studies.<sup><a href="#R23" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R23">23</a></sup> Only 46% of the mothers breastfed, and this percentage waned over the course of the study as mothers began to introduce solid foods.</p>
