</div></div></section><p id="P11"><a href="#F1" class="usa-link">Figure 1</a> presents discrete-time Kaplan-Meier plots for the three milestones for two groups formed by a median split of the AHEI-P maternal diet quality scores (low diet quality = below median; high diet quality = above median). The <em>y</em>-axis denotes the probability of <em>not</em> achieving the milestone at each month, which is the survival function in this context. Infants in the low diet quality group tended to sit up earlier than those in the high diet quality group, as indicated by the lower survival function for the low-quality group (dashed line) compared to the high-quality group (dotted line). For example, the probability of sitting up in month 3—the onset of the milestone window—was 0.08 for the low-quality group compared to 0.06 for the high-quality group. By the end of month 6, the probability of sitting up was 0.78 for the low-quality group and 0.71 in the high-quality group. As expected, all infants had probability 1 of sitting up by month 10, as this represents the upper limit of the milestone window. By contrast, there was little difference in the timing of crawling for the two groups. Finally, infants in the high-quality group tended to walk somewhat earlier than those in the low-quality group, particularly at the end of the study. For example, by the end of 12 months, the probability of walking was 0.68 for infants in the high-quality group and 0.57 for the low-quality group.</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="F1"><h3 class="obj_head">FIGURE 1.</h3>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=6445681_nihms-1000672-f0001.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/dd1a/6445681/8cc0102ecca7/nihms-1000672-f0001.jpg" loading="lazy" height="535" width="600" alt="FIGURE 1"></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/F1/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p id="P67">Kaplan-Meier plots for sitting up, crawling, and walking in the Nurture study for groups with low and high maternal diet quality. The groups were formed by a median split of the Alternate Healthy Eating Index-Pregnancy scores. Lower survival functions indicate earlier achievement [Colour figure can be viewed at <a href="http://wileyonlinelibrary.com" class="usa-link usa-link--external" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">wileyonlinelibrary.com</a>]</p></figcaption></figure></section><section id="S3"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">3 |. MULTIVARIATE DISCRETE FAILURE TIME MODEL</h2>
<p id="P12">For <em>i</em> = 1, … <em>, n</em> and <em>j</em> = 1, … <em>, J</em>, let <em>T</em><sub><em>ij</em></sub> = <em>k</em> if infant <em>i</em> achieves milestone <em>j</em> (or is censored) at month <em>k</em> since the start of the WHO milestone window. Here, <em>k</em> ranges from 1 to <em>K</em><sub><em>j</em></sub> = <em>u</em><sub><em>j</em></sub> − <em>l</em><sub><em>j</em></sub> + 1, where <em>l</em><sub><em>j</em></sub> is the lower bound of the <em>j</em>th milestone window and <em>u</em><sub><em>j</em></sub> = min(upper bound of milestone window <em>j</em>, 13). The value <em>u</em><sub><em>j</em></sub> = 13 implies that the milestone exceeds the 12-month study period. For example, according to WHO guidelines, sitting up without assistance occurs during months 3 to 10 inclusive. Thus, <em>K</em><sub>1</sub> = 10 − 3 + 1 = 8 so that <em>k</em> ranges from 1 to 8 for sitting up. Likewise, crawling occurs during months 5 to 14 (inclusive), implying that <em>u</em><sub>2</sub> = 13 and <em>K</em><sub>2</sub> = 13 − 5 + 1 = 9. Finally, because walking occurs between months 8 and 18, <em>u</em><sub>3</sub> = 13 and hence <em>K</em><sub>3</sub> = 13 − 8 + 1 = 6.</p>
<p id="P13">The discrete-time hazard, <em>π</em><sub><em>ijk</em></sub> = Pr(<em>T</em><sub><em>ij</em></sub> = <em>k</em>|<em>T</em><sub><em>ij</em></sub> ≥ <em>k</em>), is the conditional probability of achieving milestone <em>j</em> in month <em>k</em> given no prior achievement. To accommodate time-varying covariates and covariate effects (thus relaxing proportional hazard assumptions), it is common to expand the data into “person-time” format in which each row represents an at-risk time interval and the corresponding outcome is a dichotomous variable indicating whether or not the milestone was achieved in that interval.<sup><a href="#R15" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R15">15</a></sup> Specifically, let <em>Y</em><sub><em>ijk</em></sub> be a binary indicator taking the value 1 if the <em>i</em>th infant achieves milestone <em>j</em> in month <em>k</em> since the start of the milestone window. Expressed in terms of <em>Y</em><sub><em>ijk</em></sub>, the discrete hazard is given by
</p>
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD1"><tr>
<td class="formula"><math id="M1" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><mspace width="0.5em"></mspace><msub><mi>π</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">Pr</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msub><mi>Y</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mspace linebreak="newline"></mspace><mspace width="0.5em"></mspace><msub><mi>π</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>k</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">Pr</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msub><mi>Y</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>k</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>|</mo><msub><mi>Y</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>⋯</mo><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>Y</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>,</mo><mspace width="0.25em"></mspace><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>…</mo><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>K</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mspace linebreak="newline"></mspace><msub><mi>π</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><msub><mi>K</mi><mi>j</mi></msub></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><munderover><mo>∏</mo><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>K</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></munderover><mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>−</mo><msub><mi>π</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>k</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>,</mo></math></td>
<td class="label">(1)</td>
</tr></table>
<p>
where the final category <em>K</em><sub><em>j</em></sub> is achieved only if <em>Y</em><sub><em>ijk</em></sub> = 0 for all <em>k &lt; K</em><sub><em>j</em></sub>; that is, the milestone is not achieved prior to interval <em>K</em><sub><em>j</em></sub>.</p>
<p id="P14">We model <em>π</em><sub><em>ijk</em></sub> as
</p>
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD2"><tr>
<td class="formula"><math id="M2" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><mi>g</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msub><mi>π</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>k</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>η</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>k</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">x</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>k</mi></mrow><mi>T</mi></msubsup><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">β</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>λ</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><msub><mi>b</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>,</mo><mspace width="1em"></mspace><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>…</mo><mo>,</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>;</mo><mspace width="0.25em"></mspace><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>…</mo><mo>,</mo><mi>J</mi><mo>;</mo><mspace width="0.25em"></mspace><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>…</mo><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>K</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo></mrow></math></td>
<td class="label">(2)</td>
</tr></table>
<p>
where <em>g</em>(·) is a binary link function; <strong><em>x</em></strong><sub><em>ijk</em></sub> is a <em>p</em><sub><em>j</em></sub> × 1 vector of milestone-specific covariates, some of which may be time varying; <strong><em>β</em></strong><sub><em>j</em></sub> is the corresponding <em>p</em><sub><em>j</em></sub> × 1 vector of milestone-specific (and potentially time-varying) regression parameters; <em>b</em><sub><em>i</em></sub> is a normally distributed subject-specific latent factor or “frailty” term; and <strong><em>λ</em></strong><sub><em>j</em></sub> is the corresponding milestone-specific factor loading quantifying the effect of the frailty on the <em>j</em>th milestone. One can view <em>b</em><sub><em>i</em></sub> as representing unobserved subject-level factors that impact the milestones differentially through the factor loadings <strong><em>λ</em></strong><sub><em>j</em></sub>. Note that model <a href="#FD2" class="usa-link">(2)</a> reduces to a conventional random intercept model when <strong><em>λ</em></strong><sub><em>j</em></sub> = 1 for all <em>j</em>. Common choices for <em>g</em>(·) include the probit and logit link functions, both of which lead to straightforward Bayesian inference via data augmentation.<sup><a href="#R15" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R15">15</a>,<a href="#R24" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R24">24</a></sup> A complementary log-log link yields the discrete-time analog to the Cox model. Hedeker et al<sup><a href="#R14" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R14">14</a></sup> note that the three link functions tend to yield similar results in practice.</p>
<p id="P15">Suppose infant <em>i</em> achieves milestone <em>j</em> in month <em>k</em> (<em>k</em> = 1, … <em>, K</em><sub><em>j</em></sub> − 1) of the milestone window or, alternatively, is censored at month <em>k</em>. We define <strong><em>Y</em></strong><sub><em>ij</em></sub> = (0, …, 0<em>, δ</em><sub><em>ij</em></sub>)<sup><em>T</em></sup> to be a <em>k</em> × 1 response vector for milestone <em>j</em>, where <em>δ</em><sub><em>ij</em></sub> is a milestone-specific achievement indicator taking the value 1 if infant <em>i</em> achieves milestone <em>j</em> during the study and 0 if censoring occurs. Note that <em>δ</em><sub><em>ij</em></sub> = <em>Y</em><sub><em>ijk</em></sub> if <em>k</em> is the final month of observation. Censoring can arise due to dropout during the study or study completion if <em>u</em><sub><em>j</em></sub> = 13. Throughout, we assume that the censoring mechanism is noninformative, as we have no a priori reason to believe that late milestone achievers drop out more frequently than early achievers. In <a href="#S7" class="usa-link">Section 6</a>, we discuss extensions to allow for informative censoring.</p>
<p id="P16">To illustrate the response vector coding, suppose infant <em>i</em> achieves milestone <em>j</em> in month <em>k</em> = 3 of the milestone window. In this case, <em>δ</em><sub><em>ij</em></sub> = 1 and the corresponding response vector is given by <strong><em>Y</em></strong><sub><em>ij</em></sub> = (0, 0, 1)<sup><em>T</em></sup>. Conversely, for an infant who is censored at month 3, <em>δ</em><sub><em>ij</em></sub> = 0 and the corresponding response is <em>Y</em><sub><em>ij</em></sub> = (0, 0, 0)<sup><em>T</em></sup>. Likewise, an infant who achieves milestone <em>j</em> at interval <em>K</em><sub><em>j</em></sub>, ie, at the upper end of the milestone window, has (<em>K</em><sub><em>j</em></sub> − 1) × 1 response vector <strong><em>Y</em></strong><sub><em>ij</em></sub> = (0, …, 0)<sup><em>T</em></sup>, which is tantamount to censoring at month <em>K</em><sub><em>j</em></sub> − 1. The corresponding <em>k</em> × 1 linear predictor for milestone (<em>i, j</em>) is given by
</p>
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD3"><tr>
<td class="formula"><math id="M3" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><munder><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">η</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>×</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></munder><mo>=</mo><munder><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">X</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">β</mi><mi>j</mi></msub></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>×</mo><msub><mi>p</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><msub><mi>p</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><mo>×</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></munder><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>λ</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><msub><mi>b</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><msub><mn mathvariant="bold">1</mn><mi>k</mi></msub><mo>,</mo></mrow></math></td>
<td class="label">(3)</td>
</tr></table>
<p>
where <strong>1</strong><sub><em>k</em></sub> denotes a <em>k</em> × 1 vector of 1’s. The column dimension of <strong><em>X</em></strong><sub><em>ij</em></sub> and the length of <strong><em>β</em></strong><sub><em>j</em></sub>, denoted <em>p</em><sub><em>j</em></sub>, will depend on the number of months in the milestone window (ie, <em>K</em><sub><em>j</em></sub>), as well as the number of time-varying and time-invariant covariates. For example, suppose that milestone <em>j</em> occurs during a 5-month window from months 2 to 6 (inclusive) following birth, and suppose that infant <em>i</em> achieves the milestone in the third month of the window. Here, <em>K</em><sub><em>j</em></sub> = 6 − 2 + 1 = 5 and <em>k</em> = 3. Further, let <em>X</em><sub>1</sub> denote a time-varying covariate and let <em>X</em><sub>2</sub> denote a time-invariant covariate. Assuming time-varying intercepts but time-invariant covariate effects (ie, regression coefficients) for <em>X</em><sub>1</sub> and <em>X</em><sub>2</sub>, <strong><em>X</em></strong><sub><em>ij</em></sub> has dimension 3 × 6 with elements
</p>
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD4"><tr>
<td class="formula"><math id="M4" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">X</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mover><mover><mrow><mtable><mtr><mtd><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Month</mi><mspace width="0.25em"></mspace><mn>1</mn></mrow></mtd><mtd><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Month</mi><mspace width="0.25em"></mspace><mn>2</mn></mrow></mtd><mtd><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Month</mi><mspace width="0.25em"></mspace><mn>3</mn></mrow></mtd><mtd><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Month</mi><mspace width="0.25em"></mspace><mn>4</mn></mrow></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mrow><mo stretchy="true">︷</mo></mover><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Intercepts</mi></mrow></mover><mover><mover><mrow><mtable><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>X</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mtd></mtr></mtable></mrow><mrow></mrow></mover><mrow></mrow></mover><mover><mover><mrow><mtable><mtr><mtd><mspace width="1em"></mspace><msub><mi>X</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mspace width="1em"></mspace><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mspace width="1em"></mspace><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mspace width="1em"></mspace><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mtd></mtr></mtable></mrow><mrow></mrow></mover><mrow></mrow></mover></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>,</mo></mrow></math></td>
<td class="label">(4)</td>
</tr></table>
<p>
where Month 1 to Month 4 correspond to the first 4 months of the milestone window. If we further allow time-varying coefficient effects for <em>X</em><sub>1</sub> (in addition to time-varying covariate values), <strong><em>X</em></strong><sub><em>ij</em></sub> expands to dimension 3 × 9 with elements
</p>
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD5"><tr>
<td class="formula"><math id="M5" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">X</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mover><mover><mrow><mtable><mtr><mtd><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Month</mi><mspace width="0.25em"></mspace><mn>1</mn></mrow></mtd><mtd><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Month</mi><mspace width="0.25em"></mspace><mn>2</mn></mrow></mtd><mtd><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Month</mi><mspace width="0.25em"></mspace><mn>3</mn></mrow></mtd><mtd><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Month</mi><mspace width="0.25em"></mspace><mn>4</mn></mrow></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mrow><mo stretchy="true">︷</mo></mover><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Intercepts</mi></mrow></mover><mover><mover><mrow><mtable><mtr><mtd><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Month</mi><mspace width="0.25em"></mspace><mn>1</mn></mrow></mtd><mtd><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Month</mi><mspace width="0.25em"></mspace><mn>2</mn></mrow></mtd><mtd><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Month</mi><mspace width="0.25em"></mspace><mn>3</mn></mrow></mtd><mtd><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Month</mi><mspace width="0.25em"></mspace><mn>4</mn></mrow></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mrow><mo stretchy="true">︷</mo></mover><mrow><msub><mi>X</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></mover><mover><mover><mrow><mtable><mtr><mtd><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Time</mi><mspace width="0.25em"></mspace><mi mathvariant="normal">Invariant</mi></mrow></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mtd></mtr></mtable></mrow><mrow></mrow></mover><mrow><msub><mi>X</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mover></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>.</mo></math></td>
<td class="label">(5)</td>
</tr></table>
<p id="P17">The corresponding regression vector, <strong><em>β</em></strong><sub><em>j</em></sub> = (<em>β</em><sub>0<em>j</em>1</sub>, <em>β</em><sub>0<em>j</em>2</sub>, <em>β</em><sub>0<em>j</em>3</sub>, <em>β</em><sub>0<em>j</em>4</sub>, <em>β</em><sub>1<em>j</em>1</sub>, <em>β</em><sub>1<em>j</em>2</sub>, <em>β</em><sub>1<em>j</em>3</sub>, <em>β</em><sub>1<em>j</em>4</sub>, <em>β</em><sub>2<em>j</em></sub>)<sup><em>T</em></sup>, includes four intercepts representing the baseline hazards for each month, four parameters for the time-varying effect of <em>X</em><sub>1</sub>, and a parameter representing the time-invariant effect of <em>X</em><sub>2</sub>.</p>
<p id="P18">Similarly, an infant <em>i</em> who achieves milestone <em>j</em> in month <em>K</em><sub><em>j</em></sub> = 5 (the upper bound of the milestone window) will have response vector <strong><em>Y</em></strong><sub><em>i</em>1</sub> = (0, 0, 0, 0)<sup><em>T</em></sup>, indicating that the infant did not achieve the milestone in the previous 4 months of the window. Again assuming time-varying regression effects for <em>X</em><sub>1</sub>, the corresponding 4 × 9 linear predictor is
</p>
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD6"><tr>
<td class="formula"><math id="M6" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">X</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mtd><mtd><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mtd></mtr></mtable></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>.</mo></mrow></math></td>
<td class="label">(6)</td>
</tr></table>
<p id="P19">Note that the time varying parameters <strong><em>β</em></strong><sub>0<em>j</em></sub> = (<em>β</em><sub>0<em>j</em>1</sub><em>, β</em><sub>0<em>j</em>2</sub><em>, β</em><sub>0<em>j</em>3</sub><em>, β</em><sub>0<em>j</em>4</sub>)<sup><em>T</em></sup> and <strong><em>β</em></strong><sub>1<em>j</em></sub> = (<em>β</em><sub>1<em>j</em>1</sub><em>, β</em><sub>1<em>j</em>2</sub><em>, β</em><sub>1<em>j</em>3</sub><em>, β</em><sub>1<em>j</em>4</sub>)<sup><em>T</em></sup> have length <em>K</em><sub><em>j</em></sub> − 1 = 4, since milestone <em>j</em> occurs with probability 1 in time interval <em>K</em><sub><em>j</em></sub> if it is not achieved in the prior <em>K</em><sub><em>j</em></sub> − 1 intervals. As a result, there are only <em>K</em><sub><em>j</em></sub> − 1 identifiable parameters for covariates with time-varying effects. The model can easily be extended to accommodate parametric functions of time (eg, linear or polynomial trends) rather than discrete period indicators as in Equations <a href="#FD5" class="usa-link">(5)</a> and <a href="#FD6" class="usa-link">(6)</a>. To ensure an identifiable model, we impose standard constraints for latent factor models,<sup><a href="#R25" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R25">25</a></sup> namely, we assume a standard normal N(0, 1) distribution for <em>b</em><sub><em>i</em></sub> and restrict the first factor loading, <strong><em>λ</em></strong><sub>1</sub>, to be positive. Finally, the <em>J</em> milestones are assumed to be conditionally independent given <em>b</em><sub><em>i</em></sub>.</p>
<section id="S4"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">3.1 |. Inference</h3>
<p id="P20">Statistical inference can be handled conveniently using either maximum likelihood or Bayesian methods. Maximum likelihood estimation (MLE) can be implemented using standard software such as the SAS<sup>®</sup> procedure NLMIXED (SAS Institute, Cary, North Carolina), which combines adaptive Gauss-Hermite quadrature for numerical integration with quasi–Newton-Raphson routines for maximization. By default, the number of quadrature points is selected adaptively, but the resulting value is often insufficient to ensure convergence for the correlated DFT model. We therefore recommend increasing the number of quadrature points using the qpoints option in NLMIXED. For the analyses below, we specified 50 quadrature points. Convergence can also be improved by adding a ridging term to the Newton-Raphson optimization routine; this can be implemented in NLMIXED by specifying tech=nrridg in the MODEL statement. Finally, the BOUNDS statement is used to impose the identifiability constraint <strong><em>λ</em></strong><sub>1</sub>
<em>&gt;</em> 0.</p>
<p id="P21">As evidenced from the simulation studies below, maximum likelihood can yield unstable estimates for small sample sizes. As an alternative, one can adopt a Bayesian approach with slightly informative priors on the factor loadings to stabilize the parameter estimates. As a default, we assign conditionally conjugate N(0, 100) priors to the regression coefficients. For the first factor loading, <strong><em>λ</em></strong><sub>1</sub>, we assign an N(0, 0.10) prior truncated below by zero to ensure identifiability; we assign unconstrained N(0, 0.10) priors to the remaining factor loadings. Based on extensive simulations, we have found that more diffuse priors for the factor loadings can lead to poor Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) convergence when the sample sizes are low. This may be due to the fact that the factor loadings scale unobserved random effects rather than fixed covariates as in the case of regression coefficients. More generally, the prior variance for <strong><em>λ</em></strong><sub><em>j</em></sub> should be chosen to stabilize the factor loading estimates when sample sizes are small. In our experience, a variance of 0.10 leads to reasonable results for relatively small sample sizes (eg, <em>n</em> = 500), with little impact for larger samples. In practice, however, we recommend sensitivity analyses to examine how different choices of prior variance impact results.</p>
<p id="P22">For probit and logit link functions, efficient data-augmented Gibbs samplers are available for posterior computation.<sup><a href="#R15" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R15">15</a>,<a href="#R24" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R24">24</a></sup> Suppose, for example, infant <em>i</em> achieves milestone <em>j</em> (or is censored) at month <em>k</em> (<em>k</em> = 1, … <em>, K</em><sub><em>j</em></sub> − 1). Under the probit link, we introduce <em>k</em> independent random variables <em>Z</em><sub><em>ij</em>1</sub>, … <em>, Z</em><sub><em>ijk</em></sub> such that <span xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><math id="M7" display="inline" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><msub><mi>Y</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn mathvariant="double-struck">1</mn><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msub><mi>Z</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow></msub><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></math></span> and <em>Z</em><sub><em>ijh</em></sub> ~ N(<em>η</em><sub><em>ijh</em></sub>, 1) for <em>h</em> = 1, … <em>k</em>, where <span xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><math id="M8" display="inline" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><mn mathvariant="double-struck">1</mn><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mo>⋅</mo><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></math></span> denotes the indicator function and <span xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><math id="M9" display="inline" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><msub><mi>η</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">x</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow><mi>T</mi></msubsup><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">β</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>λ</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><msub><mi>b</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></mrow></math></span>. The latent variable <em>Z</em><sub><em>ijh</em></sub> (<em>h</em> = 1, … <em>, k</em>) represents the underlying propensity for infant <em>i</em> to achieve milestone <em>j</em> in month <em>h</em>. Conditional on <em>b</em><sub><em>i</em></sub>, <em>Z</em><sub><em>ijh</em></sub> and <em>Z</em><sub><em>ij</em></sub>′<sub><em>h</em></sub> for milestones <em>j</em> and <em>j</em><sup>′</sup> follow independent normal distributions with unit variance. Marginally, the variance of <em>Z</em><sub><em>ijh</em></sub> is given by
</p>
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD7"><tr><td class="formula"><math id="M10" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><mtext>Var</mtext><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msub><mi>Z</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>=</mo><mtext>E</mtext><mrow><mo>[</mo><mrow><mtext>Var</mtext><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msub><mi>Z</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow></msub><mo>|</mo><msub><mi>b</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>]</mo></mrow><mo>+</mo><mtext>Var</mtext><mrow><mo>[</mo><mrow><mtext>E</mtext><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msub><mi>Z</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow></msub><mo>|</mo><msub><mi>b</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>]</mo></mrow><mspace linebreak="newline"></mspace><mspace width="4.25em"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><msubsup><mi>λ</mi><mi>j</mi><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mtext>Var</mtext><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msub><mi>b</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mspace linebreak="newline"></mspace><mspace width="4.25em"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><msubsup><mi>λ</mi><mi>j</mi><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mo>.</mo></math></td></tr></table>
<p id="P23">Similarly, the marginal covariance between <em>Z</em><sub><em>ijh</em></sub> and <em>Z</em><sub><em>ij</em></sub>′<sub><em>h</em></sub>, ie, between the latent propensity to achieve milestones <em>j</em> and <em>j</em><sup>′</sup> in month <em>h</em>, is given by
</p>
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD8"><tr><td class="formula"><math id="M11" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><mtext>Cov</mtext><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msub><mi>Z</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>Z</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><msup><mi>j</mi><mo>′</mo></msup><mi>h</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>=</mo><mtext>Cov</mtext><mrow><mo>[</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">E</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msub><mi>Z</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow></msub><mo>|</mo><msub><mi>b</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">E</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msub><mi>Z</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><msup><mi>j</mi><mo>′</mo></msup><mi>h</mi></mrow></msub><mo>|</mo><msub><mi>b</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>]</mo></mrow><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">E</mi><mrow><mo>[</mo><mrow><mtext>Cov</mtext><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msub><mi>Z</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>Z</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><msup><mi>j</mi><mo>′</mo></msup><mi>h</mi></mrow></msub><mo>|</mo><msub><mi>b</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>]</mo></mrow><mspace linebreak="newline"></mspace><mspace width="7em"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mtext>Cov</mtext><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msub><mi>λ</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><msub><mi>b</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>λ</mi><mrow><msup><mi>j</mi><mo>′</mo></msup></mrow></msub><msub><mi>b</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>+</mo><mtext>E</mtext><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mspace linebreak="newline"></mspace><mspace width="7em"></mspace><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>λ</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><msub><mi>λ</mi><mrow><msup><mi>j</mi><mo>′</mo></msup></mrow></msub><mtext>Var</mtext><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msub><mi>b</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mspace linebreak="newline"></mspace><mspace width="7em"></mspace><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>λ</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><msub><mi>λ</mi><mrow><msup><mi>j</mi><mo>′</mo></msup></mrow></msub><mo>.</mo></math></td></tr></table>
<p id="P24">Thus, while the milestones are conditionally independent given the latent frailty <em>b</em><sub><em>i</em></sub>, they are marginally correlated, with the direction of the association determined by the signs of the factor loadings <strong><em>λ</em></strong><sub><em>j</em></sub> and <strong><em>λ</em></strong><sub><em>j</em></sub>′.</p>
<p id="P25">Gibbs sampling proceeds by selecting initial values for <strong><em>β</em></strong><sub><em>j</em></sub>, <strong><em>λ</em></strong><sub><em>j</em></sub>, and <em>b</em><sub><em>i</em></sub> from <a href="#FD3" class="usa-link">Equation (3)</a> and then iterating through the following steps:</p>
<ol id="L1" class="list" style="list-style-type:decimal">
<li><div class="p" id="P26">For milestones <em>j</em> = 1, … <em>, J</em>, cycle through the following updates:
<ol id="L2" class="list" style="list-style-type:lower-alpha">
<li><div class="p" id="P27">For <em>i</em> = 1, … <em>, n</em> and <em>h</em> = 1, … <em>, k</em><sub><em>ij</em></sub>, where <em>k</em><sub><em>ij</em></sub> denotes the month of milestone achievement or censoring for infant <em>i</em> and milestone <em>j</em>, update <em>Z</em><sub><em>ijh</em></sub> from its full conditional normal distribution truncated below (above) by zero for <em>Y</em><sub><em>ijh</em></sub> = 1 (<em>Y</em><sub><em>ijh</em></sub> = 0);</div></li>
<li><div class="p" id="P28">Update <strong><em>β</em></strong><sub><em>j</em></sub> from its multivariate normal full conditional;</div></li>
<li><div class="p" id="P29">Update <strong><em>λ</em></strong><sub><em>j</em></sub> from its normal full conditional (or truncated normal for <strong><em>λ</em></strong><sub>1</sub>);</div></li>
</ol>
</div></li>
<li><p id="P30">For <em>i</em> = 1, … <em>, n</em>, update <em>b</em><sub><em>i</em></sub> from its normal full conditional.</p></li>
</ol>
<p id="P31">A related data augmentation scheme exists for a logit link; see the work of Polson et al<sup><a href="#R24" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R24">24</a></sup> for details. The <a href="#APP1" class="usa-link">Appendix</a> provides the full conditionals for implementing the Gibbs sampler under both a probit and logit link. R<sup><a href="#R26" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R26">26</a></sup> code for fitting the proposed Gibbs sampler is available at the first author’s website (<a href="http://people.musc.edu/~brn200/" class="usa-link usa-link--external" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">http://people.musc.edu/~brn200/</a>), along with Proc NLMIXED code for MLE. Convergence is monitored using standard MCMC diagnostics such as trace plots. Because the Gibbs sampler relies entirely on closed-form, conditionally conjugate updates, we typically observe rapid convergence after only a few hundred iterations of the Gibbs sampler.</p></section></section><section id="S5"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">4 |. SIMULATION STUDIES</h2>
<p id="P32">We conducted two simulation studies to assess the properties of the model and to compare the maximum likelihood and Bayesian inferential approaches. For the first study, we generated datasets of size <em>n</em> = 500 and <em>n</em> = 5000 infants from the following trivariate DFT model:
</p>
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD9"><tr>
<td class="formula"><math id="M12" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant="normal">Φ</mi><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msub><mi>π</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>k</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">x</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>k</mi></mrow><mi>T</mi></msubsup><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">β</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>λ</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><msub><mi>b</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>,</mo><mspace width="1em"></mspace><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>…</mo><mo>,</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>;</mo><mspace width="0.25em"></mspace><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>…</mo><mo>,</mo><mi>J</mi><mo>;</mo><mspace width="0.25em"></mspace><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>…</mo><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>K</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo></mrow></math></td>
<td class="label">(7)</td>
</tr></table>
<p>
where Φ<sup>−1</sup>(·) denotes the inverse standard normal CDF and <em>J</em> = 3 corresponding to 3 milestones for each infant. We assumed a total study period of 6 months. The window for milestone 1 ranged from 1 to 5 months inclusive, so that <em>K</em><sub>1</sub> = 5 − 1 + 1 = 5. Milestone 1 might correspond to a milestone such as sitting up that occurs during the first part of the study. The linear predictor for milestone 1 included time-varying intercepts for months 1 to 4, a time-invariant dichotomous covariate common to all milestones and time points (<em>X</em><sub>1</sub>), and a time-varying continuous covariate common to all milestones (<em>X</em><sub>2</sub>). The covariate effects for <em>X</em><sub>1</sub> and <em>X</em><sub>2</sub> were held constant over time. Thus, for an infant who achieved milestone 1 in month 3, the response vector was simulated as <strong><em>Y</em></strong><sub><em>i</em>1</sub> = (0, 0, 1)<sup><em>T</em></sup> and the linear predictor was generated as
</p>
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD10"><tr>
<td class="formula"><math id="M13" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><munder><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">η</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></munder><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">X</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">β</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>λ</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>b</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><msub><mn mathvariant="bold">1</mn><mn>3</mn></msub><mspace linebreak="newline"></mspace><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">X</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mi>i</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mtd><mtd><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>i</mi><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mi>i</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mtd><mtd><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>i</mi><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mi>i</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mtd><mtd><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>i</mi><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mtd></mtr></mtable></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>,</mo></math></td>
<td class="label">(8)</td>
</tr></table>
<p>
where <strong><em>β</em></strong><sub>1</sub> = (<em>β</em><sub>011</sub><em>, β</em><sub>012</sub><em>, β</em><sub>013</sub><em>, β</em><sub>014</sub><em>, β</em><sub>11</sub><em>, β</em><sub>21</sub>)<sup><em>T</em></sup>. The first 4 elements of <strong><em>β</em></strong><sub>1</sub> correspond the intercepts for months 1 to 4, <em>β</em><sub>11</sub> denotes the time-invariant effect of <em>X</em><sub>1</sub> on milestone 1, and <em>β</em><sub>21</sub> denotes the time-invariant effect of <em>x</em><sub>2<em>i</em></sub>. Similarly, we assumed that milestone 2 occurred between months 1 to 6, so that <em>K</em><sub>2</sub> = 6 − 1 + 1 = 6. Milestone 2 might represent a milestone that occurs strictly during the study period and not beyond. Lastly, we assumed that milestone 3 ranged from month 3 to month “7,” where month 7 denotes that the upper bound for milestone 3 exceeded the 6-month study period. This might represent a milestone such as walking that occurs during the latter part of the study and extends past the study period. Thus, for milestone 3, <em>u</em><sub>3</sub> = 7 and <em>K</em><sub>3</sub> = 7 − 3 + 1 = 5. The subject-level binary covariate <em>x</em><sub>1<em>i</em></sub> was generated from a Bernoulli (0.50) distribution; the subject-level time-varying covariate <em>x</em><sub>2<em>ik</em></sub> was simulated from an N(0, 1) distribution for the first 3 months of the study, and from an N(0.50, 1) distribution for months 4 to 6, indicating an increase in the mean of <em>x</em><sub>2<em>ik</em></sub> at the midpoint of the study. The subject-specific frailties, <em>b</em><sub><em>i</em></sub>, were generated from a standard normal distribution.</p>
<p id="P33">For the analysis, we fit model (7) with a probit link. For maximum likelihood inference, we used SAS Proc NLMIXED with 50 quadrature points for numerical integration. We applied Newton-Raphson with ridging to maximize the integrated likelihood. For Bayesian inference, we implemented the data-augmented Gibbs sampler outlined in the previous section. We assigned independent N(0, 100) priors to the regression coefficients, a zero-truncated N(0, 0.10) prior for <strong><em>λ</em></strong><sub>1</sub>, and unconstrained N(0, 0.10) priors for <strong><em>λ</em></strong><sub>2</sub> and <strong><em>λ</em></strong><sub>3</sub>. We ran the Gibbs sampler for 6000 iterations, discarding the first 1000 as burn-in. MCMC diagnostics, including trace plots, indicated rapid convergence and excellent posterior mixing.</p>
<p id="P34"><a href="#F2" class="usa-link">Figure 2</a> presents the unadjusted Kaplan-Meier plots for the dataset with sample size <em>n</em> = 500. Approximately 73% of infants achieved milestone 1 in the first month. Among those remaining, the probability of achieving milestone 1 remained relatively constant at 0.23 until month 5, the upper end of the milestone window. About 29% of infants achieved milestone 2 in month 1, with small decreases in the survival function between months 3 and 5. About 30% of the infants achieved milestone 3 in month 3, the onset of the milestone window; 36% were censored at the end of the 6-month simulation study.</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="F2"><h3 class="obj_head">FIGURE 2.</h3>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=6445681_nihms-1000672-f0002.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/dd1a/6445681/9e711b781560/nihms-1000672-f0002.jpg" loading="lazy" height="535" width="600" alt="FIGURE 2"></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/F2/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p id="P68">Unadjusted Kaplan-Meier plots of motor developmental milestones in simulation study 1 with <em>n</em> = 500 [Colour figure can be viewed at <a href="http://wileyonlinelibrary.com" class="usa-link usa-link--external" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">wileyonlinelibrary.com</a>]</p></figcaption></figure><p id="P35"><a href="#T2" class="usa-link">Table 2</a> presents the parameter estimates and 95% intervals under Bayesian and MLE. For <em>n</em> = 500, the Bayesian estimates were close to the true value, with posterior credible intervals (CrIs) that generally overlapped the simulated values. The maximum likelihood estimates (MLEs), on the other hand, were less accurate, especially for milestone 1. This may be due to the fact that over 70% of the infants achieved the milestone in month 1, leaving relatively low samples for estimating remaining intercept parameters. Even with an increase to 100 quadrature points, the MLEs were imprecise, suggesting that maximum likelihood may not be the best choice for small samples. For <em>n</em> = 5000, the Bayesian and maximum likelihood estimates coincided, although the Bayesian CrIs were generally narrower than the corresponding frequentist confidence intervals. In terms of computation, there was a distinct advantage for the Bayesian approach. For <em>n</em> = 500, the Gibbs sampler took 47 seconds to run 6000 iterations on a Dell<sup>®</sup> Precision T3610 workstation. In contrast, SAS Proc NLMIXED with 50 quadrature points took approximately 9 minutes to complete. For <em>n</em> = 5000, the discrepancy in run times was even more stark: Gibbs sampling required approximately 6 minutes, whereas NLMIXED took over an hour. Thus, from a purely computational standpoint, the Bayesian approach is preferable to MLE. As a sensitivity analysis, we increased the prior variance for the factor loadings from 0.10 to 1 and obtained posterior estimates similar to the MLEs, particularly for <em>n</em> = 5000, indicating little sensitivity to prior specification for moderate to large samples.</p>
