<div class="tw-foot p">
<div class="fn" id="TFN2">
<sup>†</sup><p class="display-inline" id="P74">Posterior means and 95% credible intervals obtained from Gibbs sampler described in <a href="#S3" class="usa-link">Section 3</a>.</p>
</div>
<div class="fn" id="TFN3">
<sup>‡</sup><p class="display-inline" id="P75">Maximum likelihood estimates (MLEs) and 95% confidence intervals obtained using SAS Proc NLMIXED.</p>
</div>
<div class="fn" id="TFN4">
<sup>*</sup><p class="display-inline" id="P76">Intercepts represent baseline hazards, on the probit scale, for the first <em>K<sub>j</sub></em> – 1 months of the milestone window, where <em>K</em><sub>1</sub> = 5, <em>K</em><sub>2</sub> = 6 and <em>K</em><sub>3</sub> = 5.</p>
</div>
<div class="fn" id="TFN5">
<sup>**</sup><p class="display-inline" id="P77"><em>X</em><sub>1</sub> = Time-invariant binary covariate; <em>X</em><sub>2</sub> = Time-varying continuous covariate.</p>
</div>
</div></section><p id="P36">For the second simulation study, we extended model (7) to include two additional covariates, <em>X</em><sub>3</sub> and <em>X</em><sub>4</sub>, with time-varying coefficient effects, where <em>X</em><sub>3</sub> was generated as a time-invariant binary covariate and <em>X</em><sub>4</sub> was simulated as a 3-category, time-varying ordinal covariate. The resulting model contained 48 parameters. To test the model’s robustness to misspecification, we simulated the frailty terms, <em>b</em><sub><em>i</em></sub>, from a <em>t</em><sub>8</sub> distribution, which has heavier tails than the normal density and closely approximates a scaled logistic distribution.<sup><a href="#R27" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R27">27</a></sup> Prior specification was similar to that for simulation study 1, but we assumed a more diffuse N(0, 100) prior for the factor loadings to assess the impact of a less informative prior on the posterior estimates. We generated 5000 observations from this expanded model and used both Bayesian and MLE for inference. For Bayesian inference, we ran the Gibbs sampler for 6000 iterations, discarding the first 1000 as burn-in. For maximum likelihood, we fit the model that is Proc NLMIXED as before.</p>
<p id="P37">The results are presented in <a href="#SD1" class="usa-link">Table S1 of the Online Supplement</a>. In general, the estimates and intervals were close to the simulated values for both Bayesian and MLE, suggesting that both approaches work well even under this more challenging scenario with additional parameters and a misspecified random effect distribution. Of note, however, the Gibbs sampler took approximately 6 minutes to run, whereas NLMIXED took 1.25 hours, indicating a practical advantage for the Bayesian approach.</p></section><section id="S6"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">5 |. ANALYSIS OF THE NURTURE DATA</h2>
<p id="P38">Next, we fit the proposed multivariate DFT model to the Nurture data. The dataset comprised 526 infants and a total of 5725 person-month observations. The model specification was similar to <a href="#FD9" class="usa-link">Equation (7)</a>. The model included the covariates presented in <a href="#T1" class="usa-link">Table 1</a>, with monthly breastfeeding status incorporated as a time-varying covariate (1 = breastfeeding during the month, 0 = not breastfeeding). Continuous predictors were standardized about their means. Prior specification was identical to that in <a href="#S5" class="usa-link">Section 4</a>. We ran the Gibbs sampler conservatively for 10 000 iterations after a burn-in of 1000. The sampler took approximately 4.5 minutes to run.</p>
<p id="P39">For model comparison, we fit a random intercept model in which <strong><em>λ</em></strong><sub><em>j</em></sub> was set to 1 for all <em>j</em>; the random effect variance, <span xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><math id="M14" display="inline" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><msubsup><mi>σ</mi><mi>b</mi><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mrow></math></span>, was left unspecified and assigned a conjugate inverse-gamma(0.01, 0.01) prior. We additionally fit a fixed effects model that excluded the subject-specific frailty term altogether. For each model, we computed the Watanabe Information Criterion (WAIC), a Bayesian model comparison measure,<sup><a href="#R28" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R28">28</a></sup> with lower values indicating better model fit. The WAIC value for the proposed multivariate DFT model was 4476; the WAIC values for the random intercept and fixed effects models were 4553 and 4758, respectively, indicating superior fit for the proposed model. Lastly, we fit model (7) with a logit rather than probit link and obtained a WAIC value of 4520, suggesting better fit for the probit version of the model.</p>
<p id="P40"><a href="#F3" class="usa-link">Figure 3</a> shows the estimated baseline hazards (intercepts) on the probit scale for the 3 milestones: sitting up, crawling, and walking. Each milestone has <em>K</em><sub><em>j</em></sub> − 1 intercepts, where <em>K</em><sub><em>j</em></sub> = 8 for sitting up, 9 for crawling, and 6 for walking. The horizontal dashed line represents the point at which the reference covariate group exceeds 0.50 probability of achieving the milestone, conditional on no prior achievement. Overall, we observe increasing trends in the baseline hazards for the 3 milestones, reflecting our intuition that the conditional probability of achieving a milestone should generally increase over time until the final month of the milestone window, at which point the conditional probability is 1, as infants must achieve milestone <em>j</em> at interval <em>K</em><sub><em>j</em></sub> if not before. However, it is possible to observe local decreases or flat regions corresponding to intervals of relatively constant hazard on the probit scale, particularly during months of peak milestone achievement. For sitting up, the baseline hazard increased steadily from month 3 (the start of the milestone window) through month 6 before leveling off during months 7 and 8, the period during which most infants sit up. Similarly, the baseline hazard for crawling increased steadily from months 5 to 9, followed by an interval of relatively constant hazard between months 10 and 11. The large intercept for crawling at month 12 indicates that few infants in the reference group crawled beyond month 12. Finally, the baseline hazard of walking increased from months 8–12, reflecting the fact that infants tend to walk around their first birthday.</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="F3"><h3 class="obj_head">FIGURE 3.</h3>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=6445681_nihms-1000672-f0003.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/dd1a/6445681/c1c2d02f2c55/nihms-1000672-f0003.jpg" loading="lazy" height="542" width="600" alt="FIGURE 3"></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/F3/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p id="P69">Estimated baseline hazards (intercepts) on probit scale for sitting up, crawling, and walking from the Nurture study. Dashed horizontal line denotes the point at which the baseline hazard probability exceeds 0.50. Each milestone has <em>K</em><sub><em>j</em></sub> − 1 intercepts, where <em>K</em><sub><em>j</em></sub> = 8 for sitting up, 9 for crawling, and 6 for walking [Colour figure can be viewed at <a href="http://wileyonlinelibrary.com" class="usa-link usa-link--external" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">wileyonlinelibrary.com</a>]</p></figcaption></figure><p id="P41"><a href="#T3" class="usa-link">Table 3</a> presents the posterior means and 95% CrIs for the infant and maternal covariates included in the model. AHEI-P diet score was negatively associated with sitting up, but positively associated with both crawling and, in particular, walking (posterior mean = 0.09; 95% CrI = [0.00, 0.19]). Moreover, infants born to older mothers showed delayed sitting up. Lastly, black race was associated with earlier motor development for all 3 milestones.</p>
<section class="tw xbox font-sm" id="T3"><h3 class="obj_head">TABLE 3.</h3>
<div class="caption p"><p id="P78">Posterior means and 95% credible intervals (CrIs) from the analysis of the Nurture data</p></div>
<div class="tbl-box p" tabindex="0"><table class="content" frame="void" rules="none">
<colgroup span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
</colgroup>
<thead><tr>
<th align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Milestone</th>
<th align="center" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Variable</th>
<th align="center" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Posterior Mean</th>
<th align="center" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">95% CrI</th>
</tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
