<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/T3/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<div class="tw-foot p">
<div class="fn" id="TFN6">
<sup>†</sup><p class="display-inline" id="P79">Monthly indicator ofbreastfeeding status (yes/no).</p>
</div>
<div class="fn" id="TFN7"><p id="P80">Abbreviation: AHEI-P, Alternate Healthy Eating Index-Pregnancy.</p></div>
</div></section><p id="P42">Next, we estimated survival functions for 2 maternal diet quality groups: the first with an AHEI-P score 1 standard deviation (SD) above the sample mean (high diet quality), and the second with an AHEI-P score 1 SD below the sample mean (low diet quality). To construct the estimates, we used the “standardization” method,<sup><a href="#R29" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R29">29</a></sup>whereby we first assumed that each infant belonged to the high-quality group, obtained a predicted achievement probability at each time point, and then averaged the individual-level predictions to obtain average monthly achievement probabilities for the high-quality population. We repeated the process by next assuming each infant belonged to the low-quality group. The results are presented in <a href="#F4" class="usa-link">Figure 4</a>. As indicated by the lower survival function, higher diet quality was associated with later sitting up but earlier crawling and walking, confirming the results reported in <a href="#T3" class="usa-link">Table 3</a>. In particular, according to these estimates, an infant in the high-quality group (dotted line) has a 70% (95% CrI = [64, 76]) chance of walking in the first year of life, whereas an infant in the low-quality group (dashed line) has only a 62% (95% CrI = [56, 69]) chance, for a net difference of 8 percentage points (95% CrI = [0, 16]).</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="F4"><h3 class="obj_head">FIGURE 4.</h3>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=6445681_nihms-1000672-f0004.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/dd1a/6445681/a97b8a529541/nihms-1000672-f0004.jpg" loading="lazy" height="541" width="600" alt="FIGURE 4"></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/F4/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p id="P70">Estimated survival functions for two maternal diet quality groups: high quality = AHEI-P score 1 SD above the sample mean (dotted line); low quality = AHEI-P score 1 SD below sample mean (dashed line). Lower survival functions indicate earlier achievement. AHEI-P, Alternate Healthy Eating Index-Pregnancy; SD, standard deviation [Colour figure can be viewed at <a href="http://wileyonlinelibrary.com" class="usa-link usa-link--external" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">wileyonlinelibrary.com</a>]</p></figcaption></figure><p id="P43"><a href="#SD1" class="usa-link">Table S1 and Figures S1-S3 in the Online Supplement</a> provide additional comparisons between the proposed latent factor model with milestone-specific factor loadings and the random intercept model with <strong><em>λ</em></strong><sub><em>j</em></sub> = 1 for all <em>j</em>. The models differed modestly in terms of their fixed effect estimates and intervals (<a href="#SD1" class="usa-link">Table S2</a>), particularly their estimates for race. They also differed noticeably in terms of their baseline hazard estimates (<a href="#SD1" class="usa-link">Figure S1</a>), with the random intercept showing earlier sitting up but delayed crawling relative to the proposed model. There were slight differences in the population average Kaplan-Meier curves (<a href="#SD1" class="usa-link">Figure S2</a>), but in general, the results were similar for the two models. However, there were noteworthy differences for specific individuals, suggesting different degrees of between-subject heterogeneity across the models. <a href="#SD1" class="usa-link">Figure S3</a> shows the difference in the Kaplan-Meier curves under the two models for a randomly selected infant (ID = 139). For this infant, the random intercept model showed earlier achievement of sitting up, but delayed crawling and (to a lesser extent) walking compared to the proposed latent factor model. These results suggest that the choice of model can have a clinically meaningful impact on results.</p></section><section id="S7"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">6 |. DISCUSSION</h2>
<p id="P44">We have proposed a multivariate DFT model for the analysis of correlated motor developmental milestones. The model accounts for within-subject association, while simultaneously allowing differential covariate effects across milestones. The model also accommodates different developmental windows for each milestone. We implemented both frequentist and Bayesian approaches for inference. For Bayesian inference, we developed a straightforward Gibbs sampler that relies entirely on closed-form full conditionals under either a probit or logit link. Our simulations suggest that the Bayesian approach provides accurate posterior estimates for a variety of sample sizes and may be preferable for studies with small samples. It is also superior to maximum likelihood in terms of computation time, as the latter typically requires a large number of quadrature points to ensure convergence.</p>
<p id="P45">To our knowledge, this is the first study to examine associations between overall maternal diet quality and motor milestone achievement in infants. Our analysis revealed that higher maternal diet quality was associated with earlier crawling and walking, but somewhat delayed sitting up. These associations could be operating through a number of mechanisms. One previous study found a relationship between higher diet quality and reduced risk of small for gestational age infants,<sup><a href="#R30" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R30">30</a></sup> a potential risk factor for delayed motor achievement. Better diet quality in pregnancy could also influence muscle development in utero and, in turn, impact motor development during the first year of life. These results also have important clinical implications for improving infant motor development. For example, pediatricians and other health professionals can monitor diet quality during pregnancy and make recommendations to promote earlier motor development. They might also assess the rate of gross motor achievement in infancy and use this information as a potential marker of developmental delays. Finally, understanding factors that influence motor achievement as a whole rather than each milestone individually could help clinicians design interventions to target the mechanisms underlying all milestones.</p>
<p id="P46">There are a number of areas for future work. For example, some infants may not manifest earlier milestones, such as crawling, but instead progress directly to the next developmental milestone. The proposed model could therefore be extended to allow for latent transition states. While our application limited milestone achievement to WHO-recommended developmental windows, in general, this is not necessary if no such restrictions apply. Unrestricted models would in fact be more straightforward to fit. The model could also be expanded to accommodate informative censoring by jointly modeling the dropout and discrete survival processes.<sup><a href="#R31" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R31">31</a></sup> Although we adopted a shared-parameter approach with a single random effect for all milestones, in longitudinal settings, one could incorporate milestone-specific random effects that are correlated across milestones through a multidimensional covariance matrix. Finally, the random effects could be modeled via skew-normal or skew-<em>t</em> distributions<sup><a href="#R32" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R32">32</a></sup> to accommodate potential departures from normality. More generally, the methods developed here could be applied to clinical settings where interest lies in jointly modeling correlated discrete or grouped time-to-event data.</p></section><section id="SM1"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Supplementary Material</h2>
<section class="sm xbox font-sm" id="SD1"><div class="caption p"><span>1</span></div>
<div class="media p" id="d36e3777"><div class="caption">
<a href="/articles/instance/6445681/bin/NIHMS1000672-supplement-1.pdf" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" class="usa-link">NIHMS1000672-supplement-1.pdf</a><sup> (192.2KB, pdf) </sup>
</div></div></section></section><section id="S8" class="ack"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">ACKNOWLEDGEMENTS</h2>
<p id="P47">This work was supported through grants UG3OD023316 and R01DK094841 from the National Institutes of Health (NIH). The content is solely the responsibility of the authors and does not necessarily represent the official views of NIH.</p>
<p id="P48">Funding information</p>
<p id="P49">National Institutes of Health, Grant/Award Number: UG3OD023316 and R01DK094841</p></section><section id="APP1" class="app"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">APPENDIX</h2>
<p id="P50">Here, we provide the full conditional updates for implementing the Gibbs sampler described in <a href="#S3" class="usa-link">Section 3</a>. We initialize the sampler by choosing values for <strong><em>β</em></strong><sub><em>j</em></sub>( <em>j</em> = 1, … <em>, J</em>), <strong><em>λ</em></strong><sub><em>j</em></sub>( <em>j</em> = 1, … <em>, J</em>), and <em>b</em><sub><em>i</em></sub>(<em>i</em> = 1, … <em>, n</em>). Under a probit link, we iterate through the following steps.</p>
<ol id="L3" class="list" style="list-style-type:decimal">
<li><div class="p" id="P51">For milestones <em>j</em> = 1, … <em>, J</em>, cycle through the following updates.
<ol id="L4" class="list" style="list-style-type:lower-alpha">
<li><div class="p" id="P52">For <em>i</em> = 1, … <em>, n</em> and <em>h</em> = 1, … <em>, k</em><sub><em>ij</em></sub>, where <em>k</em><sub><em>ij</em></sub> denotes the month of milestone achievement or censoring for infant <em>i</em> and milestone <em>j</em>, update <em>Z</em><sub><em>ijh</em></sub> from its N(<strong><em>η</em></strong><sub><em>ijh</em></sub>, 1) full conditional truncated below (above) by zero for <em>Y</em><sub><em>ijh</em></sub> = 1(<em>Y</em><sub><em>ijh</em></sub> = 0), where <span xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><math id="M15" display="inline" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><msub><mi>η</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">x</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow><mi>T</mi></msubsup><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">β</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>λ</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><msub><mi>b</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></mrow></math></span>.</div></li>
<li>
<div class="p" id="P53">Assuming an <span xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><math id="M16" display="inline" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><msub><mtext>N</mtext><mrow><msub><mi>p</mi><mi>j</mi></msub></mrow></msub><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">β</mi><mrow><mn>0</mn><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi mathvariant="normal">Σ</mi><mrow><mn>0</mn><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></math></span> prior for <strong><em>β</em></strong><sub><em>j</em></sub>, update <strong><em>β</em></strong><sub><em>j</em></sub> from its <span xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><math id="M17" display="inline" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><msub><mtext>N</mtext><mrow><msub><mi>p</mi><mi>j</mi></msub></mrow></msub><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">μ</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi mathvariant="normal">Σ</mi><mi>j</mi></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></math></span> full conditional, where
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD11"><tr><td class="formula"><math id="M18" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><msub><mi mathvariant="normal">Σ</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msubsup><mi mathvariant="normal">Σ</mi><mrow><mn>0</mn><mi>j</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msubsup><mo>+</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">X</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>T</mi></msubsup><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">X</mi><mi>j</mi></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mspace width="1.5em"></mspace><mi>and</mi><mspace linebreak="newline"></mspace><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">μ</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant="normal">Σ</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><mrow><mo>[</mo><mrow><msubsup><mi mathvariant="normal">Σ</mi><mrow><mn>0</mn><mi>j</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msubsup><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">β</mi><mrow><mn>0</mn><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>+</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">X</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>T</mi></msubsup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">Z</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><mo>−</mo><msub><mi>λ</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">B</mi><mi>j</mi></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>]</mo></mrow><mo>.</mo></math></td></tr></table>
</div>
<div class="p" id="P54">Here, <strong><em>X</em></strong><sub><em>j</em></sub> is an <em>N</em><sub><em>j</em></sub> × <em>p</em><sub><em>j</em></sub> design matrix for milestone <em>j</em>, <span xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><math id="M19" display="inline" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">Z</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msup><mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msub><mi>Z</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mi>j</mi><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>…</mo><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>Z</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mi>j</mi><msub><mi>k</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>…</mo><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>Z</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>j</mi><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>…</mo><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>Z</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>j</mi><msub><mi>k</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow><mi>T</mi></msup></mrow></math></span> is an <em>N</em><sub><em>j</em></sub> × 1 vector of all latent normal variables for milestone <em>j</em>, <span xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><math id="M20" display="inline" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><msub><mi>N</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mo>∑</mo><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>n</mi></msubsup><mrow><msub><mi>k</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mrow></math></span> is the total number of person-months in the sample for milestone <em>j</em>, and <strong><em>B</em></strong><sub><em>j</em></sub> is an <em>N</em><sub><em>j</em></sub> × 1 concatenated vector of frailty terms, with <em>b</em><sub><em>i</em></sub> repeated <em>k</em><sub><em>ij</em></sub> times for <em>i</em> = 1, … <em>, n</em>. For the analyses presented in this paper, we chose <strong><em>β</em></strong><sub>0<em>j</em></sub> = <strong>0</strong> and <span xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><math id="M21" display="inline" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant="normal">Σ</mi><mrow><mn>0</mn><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>100</mn><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">I</mi><mrow><msub><mi>p</mi><mi>j</mi></msub></mrow></msub></mrow></math></span>.</div>
</li>
<li>
<div class="p" id="P55">Assuming an <span xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><math id="M22" display="inline" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><mtext>N</mtext><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><msubsup><mi>τ</mi><mi>λ</mi><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msubsup></mrow><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></mrow></math></span> prior, update <strong><em>λ</em></strong><sub><em>j</em></sub> from its <span xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><math id="M23" display="inline" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><mtext>N</mtext><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mrow><msub><mi>μ</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><mo>,</mo><msubsup><mi>σ</mi><mi>j</mi><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mrow><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></mrow></math></span> full conditional (or truncated normal for <strong><em>λ</em></strong><sub>1</sub>), where
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD12"><tr><td class="formula"><math id="M24" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><msubsup><mi>σ</mi><mi>j</mi><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mo>=</mo><msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msub><mi>τ</mi><mi>λ</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><munderover><mo>∑</mo><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>n</mi></munderover><mrow><msub><mi>k</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><msubsup><mi>b</mi><mi>i</mi><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mspace width="2em"></mspace><mtext>and</mtext><mspace linebreak="newline"></mspace><msub><mi>μ</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mi>σ</mi><mi>j</mi><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">b</mi><mi>T</mi></msup><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">u</mi><mi>j</mi></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>.</mo></math></td></tr></table>
</div>
<div class="p" id="P56">Here, <strong><em>b</em></strong> = (<em>b</em><sub>1</sub>, … <em>, b</em><sub><em>n</em></sub>)<sup><em>T</em></sup> and <span xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><math id="M25" display="inline" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">u</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msup><mrow><mrow><mo>[</mo><mrow><msubsup><mo>∑</mo><mrow><mi>h</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>k</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></msubsup><mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msub><mi>Z</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mi>j</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">x</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mi>j</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow><mi>T</mi></msubsup><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">β</mi><mi>j</mi></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>,</mo><mo>…</mo><mo>,</mo><msubsup><mo>∑</mo><mrow><mi>h</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>k</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></msubsup><mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msub><mi>Z</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">x</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow><mi>T</mi></msubsup><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">β</mi><mi>j</mi></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></mrow><mo>]</mo></mrow></mrow><mi>T</mi></msup></mrow></math></span> is a vector of length <em>n</em> × 1.</div>
</li>
</ol>
</div></li>
<li><div class="p" id="P57">Assuming an N(0, 1) prior, update <em>b</em><sub><em>i</em></sub>(<em>i</em> = 1, … <em>, n</em>) from its N(<em>m</em><sub><em>i</em></sub><em>, v</em><sub><em>i</em></sub>) full conditional, where
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD13"><tr><td class="formula"><math id="M26" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><mspace width="0.5em"></mspace><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><munderover><mo>∑</mo><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>J</mi></munderover><mrow><msubsup><mi>λ</mi><mi>j</mi><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mrow><msub><mi>k</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mspace linebreak="newline"></mspace><msub><mi>m</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mrow><mo>[</mo><mrow><munderover><mo>∑</mo><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>J</mi></munderover><mrow><msub><mi>λ</mi><mi>j</mi></msub></mrow><msub><mi>u</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><mo>]</mo></mrow><mspace width="1.5em"></mspace><mtext>and</mtext><mspace linebreak="newline"></mspace><msub><mi>u</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><munderover><mo>∑</mo><mrow><mi>h</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>k</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></munderover><mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msub><mi>Z</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">x</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow><mi>T</mi></msubsup><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">β</mi><mi>j</mi></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>.</mo></math></td></tr></table>
</div></li>
</ol>
<p id="P58">For a logit link, we make the following minor modifications to the sampler.</p>
<ol id="L5" class="list" style="list-style-type:decimal">
<li><div class="p" id="P59">For milestones <em>j</em> = 1, … <em>, J</em>, cycle through the following updates.
<ol id="L6" class="list" style="list-style-type:lower-alpha">
<li><div class="p" id="P60">For <em>i</em> = 1, … <em>, n</em> and <em>h</em> = 1, … <em>, k</em><sub><em>ij</em></sub>, draw latent weights <em>w</em><sub><em>ijh</em></sub> from a Pólya-Gamma PG(1, <strong><em>η</em></strong><sub><em>ijh</em></sub>) distribution and set <em>Z</em><sub><em>ijh</em></sub> = (<em>Y</em><sub><em>ijh</em></sub> − 1∕2)∕<em>w</em><sub><em>ijh</em></sub>. For details on the PG distribution, see the work of Polson et al.<sup><a href="#R24" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R24">24</a></sup> Samples from the PG distribution can be generated efficiently using the rpg function from the R package BayesLogit.<sup><a href="#R24" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R24">24</a></sup>
</div></li>
<li><div class="p" id="P61">Update <strong><em>β</em></strong><sub><em>j</em></sub> from its <span xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><math id="M27" display="inline" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><msub><mtext>N</mtext><mrow><msub><mi>p</mi><mi>j</mi></msub></mrow></msub><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">μ</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi mathvariant="normal">Σ</mi><mi>j</mi></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></math></span> full conditional, where
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD14"><tr><td class="formula"><math id="M28" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><msub><mi mathvariant="normal">Σ</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msubsup><mi mathvariant="normal">Σ</mi><mrow><mn>0</mn><mi>j</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msubsup><mo>+</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">X</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>T</mi></msubsup><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">W</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">X</mi><mi>j</mi></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mspace linebreak="newline"></mspace><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">μ</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant="normal">Σ</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><mrow><mo>[</mo><mrow><msubsup><mi mathvariant="normal">Σ</mi><mrow><mn>0</mn><mi>j</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msubsup><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">β</mi><mrow><mn>0</mn><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>+</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">X</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>T</mi></msubsup><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">W</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">Z</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><mo>−</mo><msub><mi>λ</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">B</mi><mi>j</mi></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>]</mo></mrow><mo>,</mo></math></td></tr></table>
and <strong><em>W</em></strong><sub><em>j</em></sub> is an <em>N</em><sub><em>j</em></sub> × <em>N</em><sub><em>j</em></sub> diagonal matrix of weights <em>w</em><sub><em>ijh</em></sub> for milestone <em>j</em>.</div></li>
<li>
<div class="p" id="P62">Update <strong><em>λ</em></strong><sub><em>j</em></sub> from its <span xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><math id="M29" display="inline" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><mtext>N</mtext><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mrow><msub><mi>μ</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><mo>,</mo><msubsup><mi>σ</mi><mi>j</mi><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mrow><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></mrow></math></span> full conditional (or truncated normal for <strong><em>λ</em></strong><sub>1</sub>), where
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD15"><tr><td class="formula"><math id="M30" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><msubsup><mi>σ</mi><mi>j</mi><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mo>=</mo><msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msub><mi>τ</mi><mi>λ</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><munderover><mo>∑</mo><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>n</mi></munderover><mrow><msub><mi>w</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><msubsup><mi>b</mi><mi>i</mi><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mspace width="2em"></mspace><mtext>and</mtext><mspace linebreak="newline"></mspace><msub><mi>μ</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mi>σ</mi><mi>j</mi><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">b</mi><mi>T</mi></msup><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">u</mi><mi>j</mi></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>.</mo></math></td></tr></table>
</div>
<div class="p" id="P63">Here, <span xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><math id="M31" display="inline" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><msub><mi>w</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mo>∑</mo><mrow><mi>h</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>k</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></msubsup><mrow><msub><mi>w</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mrow></math></span> and <span xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><math id="M32" display="inline" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">u</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msup><mrow><mrow><mo>[</mo><mrow><msubsup><mo>∑</mo><mrow><mi>h</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>k</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></msubsup><mrow><msub><mi>w</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mi>j</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msub><mi>Z</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mi>j</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">x</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mi>j</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow><mi>T</mi></msubsup><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">β</mi><mi>j</mi></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>,</mo><mo>…</mo><mo>,</mo><msubsup><mo>∑</mo><mrow><mi>h</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>k</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></msubsup><mrow><msub><mi>w</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow></msub><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msub><mi>Z</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">x</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow><mi>T</mi></msubsup><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">β</mi><mi>j</mi></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></mrow><mo>]</mo></mrow></mrow><mi>T</mi></msup></mrow></math></span>.</div>
</li>
</ol>
</div></li>
<li><div class="p" id="P64">Update <em>b</em><sub><em>i</em></sub> (<em>i</em> = 1, … <em>, n</em>) from its N(<em>m</em><sub><em>i</em></sub><em>, v</em><sub><em>i</em></sub>) full conditional, where
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD16"><tr><td class="formula"><math id="M33" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><mspace width="0.5em"></mspace><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><munderover><mo>∑</mo><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>J</mi></munderover><mrow><msubsup><mi>λ</mi><mi>j</mi><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mrow><msub><mi>w</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mspace linebreak="newline"></mspace><msub><mi>m</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mrow><mo>[</mo><mrow><munderover><mo>∑</mo><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>J</mi></munderover><mrow><msub><mi>λ</mi><mi>j</mi></msub></mrow><msub><mi>u</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><mo>]</mo></mrow><mspace linebreak="newline"></mspace><msub><mi>w</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><munderover><mo>∑</mo><mrow><mi>h</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>k</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></munderover><mrow><msub><mi>w</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><mspace width="1em"></mspace><mtext>and</mtext><mspace linebreak="newline"></mspace><msub><mi>u</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><munderover><mo>∑</mo><mrow><mi>h</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>k</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></munderover><mrow><msub><mi>w</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msub><mi>Z</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">x</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow><mi>T</mi></msubsup><msub><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">β</mi><mi>j</mi></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>.</mo></math></td></tr></table>
</div></li>
</ol></section><section id="fn-group1" class="fn-group"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Footnotes</h2>
<div class="fn-group p font-secondary-light font-sm"><div class="fn p" id="FN1">
<p id="P65">SUPPORTING INFORMATION</p>
<p id="P66">Additional supporting information may be found online in the Supporting Information section at the end of the article.</p>
</div></div></section><section id="ref-list1" class="ref-list"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">REFERENCES</h2>
